@node "Mdoor" "MV Mail - Configuration - Mail Door "
@next SMB
@prev Config
        Mad Virgin Mail Door has few config files.

You MUST create directory @{b}Doors:mv/Mail@{ub}, @{b}Doors:mv/Mail/SMBCFG@{ub},
@{b}Doors:mv/mail/UserCfg@{ub} & @{b}Doors:mv/mail/blt@{ub} directories (you may use suplied
@{" install " link "Install" 0} script to create them)

     Config files :

          (located at doors:mv/mail/ directory)
    - @{" MAIL.CFG  " link "mail.cfg" 0} - External util : @{fg shine} DayDream:utils/Operatorconfig@{fg text}
    - @{" MAIL.TAGS " link "mail.tags.cfg" 0} - external
    - @{" MAIL.NET  " link "mail.net.cfg" 0} - external
    - @{"DISPLAY.CFG" link "mail.display.cfg" 0} - external
    
    Also, there is a Doors:MV/MAIL/DISPLAY directory.
    You have to create in this directories same as in your DayDream:Display/
    directory and to put files


     (located at doors:mv/mail/usercfg/ directory)
    - @{" USER.CFG  " link "USER.CFG" 0} - internal
    - @{" USER.PPA  " link "USER.ppa" 0} - internal

     (located at doors:mv/mail/blt/ directory)
    - Your @{" BULLETINS " Link Bulletins} 

(@{b}internal@{ub} means that you (user) create it from door, 
 @{b}external@{ub} means that you have to use some txt editor to create/edit them)

 Carefuly analyse example external config files in all these dirs,
 change it (and rename too) to match your configuration.



@endnode

@node SMB "MV Mail - Configuration - New Select message bases door"
@next ddconfig
@prev Mdoor

@{fg shine} It is highly recommended to replace old DayDream's SM command with this door.
       (Configure your DayDream as described in @{" DD Config" link ddconfig}.@{fg text}

     In any case, door will always use it's own SM command when user 
                    call @{" S " Link main.s} option in main menu

New SMB command allow you to configure 'special' status for each msg base.
You may disable some msg bases, make some READ ONLY or force to your users

If you wish to do so, you only have to configure some of folowing files
in : Doors:MV/MAIL/SMBCFG/ (if you use supplied @{" Installer " Link install} it will
make dir and put some examples)

 * SMB.CFG   - main (general) config file
               If you not specify any other, this file will be used for ALL
               users [except user with acces level 255 - Sysop)

 * SMB.xxx   - config file which will be used for all users with acces 
               level xxx.  If you want to define SM configuration for users
               you have to create file SMB.010 (pay atention, you must use
               THREE digits - if level is 5 you must save SMB.005, etc..)

 * SMB.yyyyy - Config file for specified single user.
               yyyyy replace with user's slot number (you @{b}must@{ub} use
               five digits in file name, i.e. for user which slot number is
               52 you must create SMB.00052 file) 


You have to put in this files only 'special' conferences, conferences
which you want to behaive normal, just forget in this files.

All these config files have following format :

x:y ----<EOL>

which means 

 x = conference number
 y = msg base number
 
 
---- are flags. At the moment door use three positions, and a last one 
     is reserved for future development (Any sugestion ? O:) )


   First flag
   -------------
   F - This message base will be always turned ON
   D - This message base will be always turned OFF
   - - Flag is not set - normal behaivour of message base.

   Second flag
   --------------
   R - This message base is READ ONLY, and user's BlueWave compatibile OLR
       will not allow writing to this conference.
       Also, for security reasons, MV Mail will check this flag while 
       importing uploaded message, and prevent user to write in this msg base.
   - - Flag is not set - user may write in this message base.

   Third flag
   --------------
   A - In this message base user may use both REAL NAMES or HANDLE.
   - - Flag is not set - user may write in this message base.
    


<EOL>= End of line (ENTER). Pay attention not to put any char behind flags,
       or door may disunderstand your config.


Example SMB config file
------- cut -------------
1:1 F-A- 
2:5 -R-- 
3:6 D--- 
3:7 D--- 
4:2 FR-- 
------- cut -------------

This means : 

 Message base 1 in conference 1 is forced to all users, and use may use
                                both real name or handle when writting
 Message base 5 in conference 2 is read only
 Message base 6 in conference 3 is disabled for users
 Message base 7 in conference 3 is disabled for users
 Message base 2 in conference 4 is forced and read only for all users

@endnode

@node LRP "MV Mail - LAST READ POINTERS door"

 Mad Virgin LRP door !
--------------------------

               @{" INSTALATION " link lrp_install}
               @{"  ABOUT IT   " link lrp_about}
               @{"    USAGE    " link lrp_usage}

@endnode

@node lrp_install "MV Mail - LAST READ POINTERS door - Instalation"

 At first you have to install MVLRP in your Doors:MV/LRP/ and
 Doors:MV/LRP/DATAs/ direcorys.
 (automaticaly done if you use supplied INSTALLER to do it)

 Also you have to add in your LogOnDoors.DAT file a line
 Doors:MV/LRP/GLRPW %N

@endnode

@node lrp_about "MV Mail - LAST READ POINTERS door - About LRP"

MV_LRP door is utility with purpose to help users to easyly set their
                           Last read pointers.

It allow users to set pointers globaly by days or number of messages

To do this, you have to install it propertly, so once a day door will
save all higher message values in Doors:MV/LRP/DATAs/current_date file.

@endnode

@node lrp_usage "MV Mail - LAST READ POINTERS door - Usage"

  When user start LRP it got following menu :
------------------------------------------------------------------------------
    :::::     :::::     > [1] Set LRP for this message base <  :::::     :::::
...::: :::   ::: :::.../  [2] Global LRP settings            \::: :::   ::: :::.
:::::   ::: :::   :::::\  [3] Individual LRP settings        /::   ::: :::   :::
         :::::          > [4] Global, by day, LRP settings  <       :::::
          :::          /                                     \       :::
           :           \  [Q] Go back to BBS                 /        :
------------------------------------------------------------------------------

 1 - Set LRP in current message base
 
 2 - Global LRP settings, a given value will be putted as LRP in ALL bases

 3 - Door will prompt user for each message base to enter LRP number.
     A current LrP value is promprted to user.
     If you enter EMPTY string you will ABORT procedure.
 
 4 - Most powerfull option - 
     Door will ask you to enter number of days backward you wish to set your
     LRPs to.
     If you enter 0 door will asume current day.

 -----------
 !IMPORTANT!
 -----------
     If you enter EMPTY string you will ABORT any door action in all of
     these cases.

@endnode


@node "mail.cfg" "MV Mail - Config files - MAIL.CFG"

    MAIL.CFG  (* Doors:MV/MAIL/MAIL.CFG)
    --------

Door will make this config when you enter Sysop config for a first time.

In version 1.30 we putted SYSOP CONFIG as an external util with GUI.
After instalation @{b}OPERATORCONFIG@{ub} is located in DayDream:Utils 
directory.


When you start OPERATORCONFIG, you will be prompt for :

Mail packet name            : name of mail packets for your system
                                   (8 chars maximum) 

Lha archiver command line   : command for LHA archiver
                                 (recomended config is :
                                 LHA -F -D2 -v9 a \s \s
                                 do not forget to put \s \s at the end!)

lzX archiver command line   : command for LZX archiver
                                 (recomended config is :
                                  LZX a \s \s
                                  do not forget to put \s \s at the end!)

Zip archiver command line   : command for ZIP archiver
                                 (recomended config is :
                                 Zip -1 -j \s \s
                                  do not forget to put \s \s at the end!)

unlHa archiver command line :  (recomended config is :
                                 lha -N e \s \s
                                  do not forget to put \s \s at the end!)

unlzx Archiver command line :  (recomended config is :
                                 lzx -X.@? e \s \s
                                  do not forget to put \s \s at the end!)
                                 Some troubles may occur with some versions
                                 of LZX archiver. We test it succesfuly with 
                                 LZX 1.01 (Evaluation) version.


Unzip Archiver command line : (recomended config is :
                                 unzip \s -d \s
                                  do not forget to put \s \s !)

                                 ( if you want to suppress output put 
                                   @{b}>NIL:@{ub} at the end of Archiver string)

BBS Network addres         : Main FIDO address of your system
                                   (it's not necessary to put this, but!)
                                   if you put it, this will prevent user
                                   to send NETMAIL to own system)


From MB                    : Maximal number of messages per single msg. base

Total                      : Maximal number of messages per packet

Bytes                      : Maximum lenght of .DAT file per packet

Copy buffer                : Size of copy buffer

Temp dir                   : Temp dir for packet
                             ( t: is recomended ))


           @{fg shine}@{u}            @{fg text}Switches@{fg shine}            @{uu}@{fg text}

Resume mail                : enable/disable @{b}RESUME MAIL@{ub}
                              option for users.
                              If you enable it, MV_Mail will save
                              packed mail packet in 
                              DayDream:Users/USR_SLOT_NUMBER
                              directory, and allow to resume 
                              transferig last mail packet.
                                      

dEl resumed mail           : Delete saved packet after user use
                               of @{b}R@{ub}esume command

create loG                 : Create LogFile 
                               (located at doors:mv/mail/ dir)
                               for @{b}O@{ub}p.download strip lines :

Operator Strip lines       : Strip FIDONET Kludge lines in Sysop's
                               packet

net maIl origin            : put * origin line in NetMail


Can forward                : Set CAN_FORWARD flag in mail packet.

Check NET dest             : Use MAIL.NET cfg to check Netmail
                             destination Address
                             (see @{"MAIL.NET" link mail.net.cfg} for details.)

DUBCheck                   : Check&Forbid upload of allready uploaded
                             messages n messages forward.

@endnode

@node "mail.net.cfg" "MV Mail - Config files - MAIL.NEW"

    MAIL.NET (* Doors:MV/MAIL/MAIL.NET)         [ external config ]
    --------

 If your system is attached to more than one FIDO system, you probably
 expirienced Dreamtoss less of feature to handle more than one NETMAIL
 conference when importing messages - in other words, all incoming netmails
 are stored into one single message base.
 This often cause problems, when you reply to message, you usualy forget
 to mover reply to suitable NetMail conference, and netmail will go from
 your system with wrong origin address.
 (i.e. you are attached to two FIDO_Style networks,
  One your address is 31:31/12 and second is 32:382/159
  In DreamToss.CFG you may configure just ONE netmail conference for 
  incoming netmails, and lets say that you configure it to base with
  fido_address 31:31/12, and you receive a netmail from 32:382/171
  In normal case, when you reply to it, a message will go to 32:382/171
  with 31:31/12 address ! :(
  But, now, MV Mail may automaticaly handle it, and move a message to correct
  message base, so this netmail will go with correct address)

 MVMail will fix it during uploading of new NetMail messages if you use a 
 MAIL.NET config.
 In this file you may configure MVMail to move uploaded netmails (from
 PKTNAME.NEW file) to one zone into specified message base, and netmails 
 to second zone into other message base.

 @{b}How to make it works ?@{ub}
---------------------------------------
In config file you have to specify following information :

zzz:xxx:yyy[enter]

    zzz - NetMail destination zone of uploaded message
    xxx - Conference number of message base for this zone
    yyy - message base number for NetMail base for this zone

    [enter] - you MUST enter LF (ascii #10) right next to last digit,
              otherwise door will not funktion regulary !

Example MAIL.NET file :

-----------------cut
31:9:1
32:15:7
84:14:19
-----------------cut  
This means that :


 All netmails for zone 31 will go to base  1 in conference  9
 All netmails for zone 32 will go to base  7 in conference 15
 All netmails for zone 84 will go to base 19 in conference 14

-----------------------------------------------------------------------
A new feature in MV Mail 1.30b and higher is tha sysop now have an 
oportunity to configure ALL allowed Netmail addresses.
To do this, you mast turn on CHECK NET DEST in @{"Operator config" link mail.cfg"}
and in MAIL.NET after definitions of conferences add # and list of all
allowed nodes:

example for mail.net with CHECK NET DEST option is :
------------------cut
31:9:1
32:15:7
84:14:19
#
31:31/1
31:31/10
31:31/11
31:31/12
31:31/13
31:31/14
31:31/15
32:382/100
32:382/154
32:382/159
32:382/171
32:382/173
84:500/101
84:500/102
84:500/103
84:500/104
84:500/105
------------------cut
If you do like this, users will be allowed to send netmails ONLY to
some of this addresses!

@endnode

@node "mail.tags.cfg" "MV Mail - Config files - MAIL.TAGS"

    MAIL.TAGS (* Doors:MV/MAIL/MAIL.TAGS)
    ---------
  In this config file you MUST put all conferenes on your BBS in  following
format :

xx:yy zzzzzzzzzzzzz{EOL}
xx:yy zzzzzzzz{EOL}
xx:yy zzzzz{EOL}
xx:yy zzzzzzzzzzzzzzzzz{EOL}

         xxx - conference number
         yyy - message base number
         zzz - Name of message base in Mail door 
               (it have not to be same as in your DD config.
                Maximal size is 20 characters)

       {EOL} - mean you press ENTER. Do not leave blank chars behind name

Please, take attention NOT TO PUT @{b}EMPTY@{ub} LINE AT BEGINING of this config file!

 - If you rename some message base on your BBS, and leave old name in
   MAIL.TAGS file, replys from old packets will still be tossed to this
   conference.

 - If you move some message base, you have to change number of conf/base
   in MAIL.TAGS file, or something may go wrong.

Here is an example of MAIL.TAGS file :

------ cut -----------
1:1 Newcommers
2:1 Mv.Projects
2:2 Mv.NEWS
2:3 Mv.Requests
2:4 Mv.Disscusion
2:5 Mv.Private 
------ cut -----------

    Numbers have not to be placed in order, but, it is reccomended for
    you to do like this for easyer reconfiguring later.

    You can use MAKETAGS utils to create this file, and then copy it from
    RAM: to Doors:MV/MAIL/ directory.

@endnode

@node "mail.display.cfg" " MV Mail - Config files - DISPLAY.CFG"

  DISPLAY.CFG (* Doors:MV/MAIL/DISPLAY.CFG)
  -----------

This is a new config in MV MAIL 1.30b and higher.

DISPLAY.CFG allows you to totaly control outlook of MV MAIL.

File is consist of folowing lines :

----------------------cut
#
Main_prompt_ANSI.... MV Mail - Main prompt (ANSI display modes)
Main_prompt_ASCII... MV Mail - Main prompt (TXT display modes)
Main_X_prompt_pos... X (horizontal - column) position for main prompt
Main_Y_prompt_pos... Y (vertical - row)      position for main prompt
SMB1_prompt_ANSI.... Select message bases prompt (ANSI)
SMB1_prompt_ASCII... Select message bases prompt (TXT)
SMB1_X_prompt_pos... Column for SMB prompt
SMB1_Y_prompt_pos... Row for SMB prompt
SMB1_slider_lines... Number of lines in SMB window
SMB1_marker......... SMB Marker char (only ONE! char, plus ANSI colour)
SMB1_X_marker_pos... Upper left marker position - column
SMB1_Y_marker_pos... Upper left marker position - row
SMB1_X_numbers_pos.. Upper left number position - column
SMB1_Y_numbers_pos.. Upper left number position - row
SMB1_X_line_pos..... Upper left msg. base name position - column
SMB1_Y_line_pos..... Upper left msg. base name position - row
SMB1_select_color... Colour for selected conferences
SMB1_unselect_color. Colour for unselected conferences
SMB1_forced_color... Colour for forced conferences
SMB1_reserved_color. Colour for disabled (banned) conferences
SMB1_numbers_color.. Colour for conf numbers
SMB2_prompt_ANSI.... Same as SMB1, but for Message base menu'
SMB2_prompt_ASCII... 
SMB2_X_prompt_pos... 
SMB2_Y_prompt_pos... 
SMB2_slider_lines... 
SMB2_marker......... 
SMB2_X_marker_pos... 
SMB2_Y_marker_pos... 
SMB2_X_numbers_pos.. 
SMB2_Y_numbers_pos.. 
SMB2_X_line_pos..... 
SMB2_Y_line_pos..... 
SMB2_select_color... 
SMB2_unselect_color. 
SMB2_forced_color... 
SMB2_reserved_color. 
SMB2_numbers_color.. 
#
-------------------------cut

Look at default DISPLAY.CFG and make experiment if you wish to match your 
own taste :)

@endnode

@node "user.cfg" "MV Mail - Config files - USER.TAGS"

    USER.CFG (* Doors:MV/MAIL/USERCFG/xx)       [ internal config ]
    --------

 When user run MVMail, door will create Doors:mv/mail/usercfg/slot_number
 config file to store user's configuration profile when user enter
 @{"c" link "main.c" 0}onfig option in door's main menu

 Please, do not edit manualy this files.
@endnode

@node "user.ppa" "MV Mail - Config files - USER.PPA"

   USER.PPA (* Doors:MV/MAIL/USERCFG/xx.PPA)     [ internal config ]


 This config file door create as addition for user Selected.DAT
 configuration. We wanted to keep compatibility with old format,
 and, there were no space for information if user want to download
 all or personal only messages, so Door is using/creating this file
 to do so.

@endnode

@node bulletins "MV Mail - Config files - Bulletins"

   How to put bulletins into your mail packets ?

 You have to create Doors:MV/MAIL/BLT/ directory 
 (if you use suplied @{"INSTALLER" link "Install" 0} it will do it automaticaly)

After instalation, put in this directory as many files as you want (do not
overload it, becouse users will DL all this files EVERY TIME they download
mail packets!)

All files have to be ASCII/ANSI files and names MUST be :

                               BLT?????.???

                                   or

                               NEWFILES.???

(? meant you can replace it with anny legal filename leter you want)

@{b} IMPORTANT! {ub}
If you put files with different names, they will be packed in packet, but it
will not be visible from OffLine reader, and may cause some troubles on some
systems!

@endnode

@node "ddconfig" " MV Mail - Configuration - EXTERNALCOMMANDS.DAT "
@prev SMB

 You have to put following lines into your EXTERNALCOMMANDS.DAT part
 of Daydream configuration file :

+
DOOR_COMMAND.. MAIL
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+

(of course, you may change door command name, and security parameters to 
 match your own system. If you want GOOD and maximum secure mail system
 on your BBS use MV Mail and forget DreamMail v2.0)

It is highly recomended to replace original DayDream's SM command and SETLRP
by putting following lines in config:

+
DOOR_COMMAND.. SM
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N S
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+


 (Flag S tells door to directly execute @{"Select Msg Bases" link "main.s" 0} option.


DOOR_COMMAND.. SETLRP
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N L
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+



You may enable some automatic door functions by putting folowing lines in your
config:


(automaticaly begin @{"Upload" link "main.u" 0} sequence, and quit after that)

+
DOOR_COMMAND.. MU
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N U
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+


(automaticaly begin @{"Download" link "main.d" 0} sequence, and quit after that) 

+
DOOR_COMMAND.. MD 
DOOR_TYPE..... 1 
DOOR_SECURITY. 5 
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N D 
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX 
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+

(automaticaly begin @{"Resume" link "main.r" 0} mail sequence, and quit after that)

+
DOOR_COMMAND.. MR
DOOR_TYPE..... 1
DOOR_SECURITY. 5
DOOR_EXECUTE.. DayDream:Doors/MV/MAIL/MAIL %N R
DOOR_CONFS1... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX 
DOOR_CONFS2... XXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXXX
+

@endnode

@node "user" "MV MAil - Users manual"
@prev "Config"

 We hope that users will have no problems to run this door, especialy
 in versions 1.30 or higher where you may define HELP screens for
 almost all MV MAIL functions.
 Anyway, you may supply file USER.MAN/USER.GUIDE to your users if you want.
 (It is same as @{" Main MENU " link "main.menu" 0} description)
@endnode

@node "main.menu" "MV MAil - Main menu"
@prev "user"

..:. Main menu commands ..............  .....  ...   .   . 



              The Blue Wave Mail Door for DayDream BBS Software
                    Copyright (C) 1997 by Mad Virgin group
                              All Rights Reserved


               (@{"D" link Main.d})ownload new mail        (@{"R" link Main.r})esume mail packet
               (@{"U" link Main.u})pload new replies       (@{"L" link LRP}) set lrp
               (@{"C" link Main.c})onfiguration menu       (H)elp page
               (@{"S" link Main.s})elect message areas     (@{"Q" link Main.q})uit back to BBS


Please enter your choice U/D/S/C/R/Q >
@endnode

@node "main.d" "MV Mail - Main menu - Download mail"

 This function will activate MAIL Download sequence.
 If there is no new messages for user, door will inform user.
 In case if there are new messages, but private and addressed to other
 user, Door will begin packing, and after that inform that there are no
 messages for user - it is normal behaivour, and not mailfunction of door. 

 If user set in @{"User Config" link "main.c" 0} to ask about files attached 
 to message, door will prompt user for file (or automaticaly begin transfer
 if user set in @{"User Config" link "main.c" 0} to do it during preparing
 Mail packet.

 If any limit is rech (Maximal number of messages per conference or total
 number of messages per packet or maximal size of unpacked .DAT file)
 door will inform user by putting folowing marks:

 * - Reached maximal number of messages per message base
 T - Reached maximal number of messages per one packet
 B - Reached maximal size of unpacked .DAT file

@endnode

@node "main.u" "MV Mail - Main menu - Upload mail"

 Upload  - Activating this option, Door wil prompt user to begin sending
           PKTNAME.NEW file (file name prompting is depending on protocol
           user selected in his personal setting on BBS)
           Attached files support for upload will be added soon

           During import door will check all restrictions for
           conference/base acces, and also will check if user name/alias
           in packet match name on system.

           For all NetMails door will check zone address in @{"MAIL.NET" link "mail.net.cfg" 0}
           config file and import message to suitable message base.

@endnode

@node "main.r" "MV Mail - Main menu - Resume mail packet"

 Resume last mail packet - this option is pretty useful for users
 if they have problems with carrier loss sessions (very usual problem
 in Yugoslavia :( ). If it is enabled in @{"Operators config" link "mail.cfg" 0}
 door will save packet prepared for Download to DayDream:user/Slot_number/
 directory before begin sending it.

 If you not suffer carrier loss problems, you may disable this option,
 but... be careful, becouse door will reset Last Read Pointers wather
 download was succesful or not (if anyone know how to check file transfer
 succes, please contact @{"Author" link "Author" 0}

@endnode

@node "main.c" "MV Mail - Main menu - UserConfig"
  This option will prompt folowing menu to user :

.----- User's BBS Mail Setup -----------------------------.
|                                                         |
|  1) Archiver in use ............ LHA                    |
|  2) SET Last Read Pointer ...... YES                    |
|  3) Max messages by any MB ..... 300                    |
|  4) Total number of messages ... 2000                   |
|  5) Max size of message DAT file 900000   bytes.        |
|  6) Send attached file ......... ASK                    |
|  7) Download message style ..... ALL                    |
|  8) Download my mail ? ......... YES                    |
|                                                         |
`---------------------------------------------------------'
Press (1/2/3/4/5/6/7/8/Filters/Save/Quit): 


Options are  :

 1 - Archiver in use (supported are : LHA / LZX / ZIP )

 2 - Reset LRP after Download [be careful, if you turn it off, your
     mail packet will grow larger and larger, and you will download
     same messages time after time... this option is for door testing
     purpose primary!)

 3 - Maximal number of messages per one message base
     (cannot be greater than value set in Sysop default configuration)

 4 - Maximal number of messages per one mail packet
     (cannot be greater than value set in Sysop default configuration)

 5 - Maximal lenght of uncompressed .DAT file
     (cannot be greater than value set in Sysop default configuration)

 6 - Behaviour with attached files. 
     May be set to :
                    Yes - Automaticaly send attached file when found.
                    Ask - Prompt user if he want to transfer file
                    No  - Do not prompt user, but anyway put information
                           about file in top of message body.

 7 - Download ALL or Personal ONLY messages in mail packet
     (this is setting for ALL conferences !!! If you want to
      download Personal messages only in some message bases, configure
      this in @{"Select message bases" link "SMB" 0} menu.

 8 - Download OWN messages.

 S - Save config in personal config file and quit menu
 
 Q - Quit and DO NOT save changes

 F - Filters menu

      In this menu you mau put 10 different filter keywords
      (filter means that door will strip message from packet if
       it found keyword in :

                - NONE    = Filtering disabled
                - ALL     = Message body and header from: field
                - From    = From field of message header
                - Message = Message body

@endnode

@node main.s "MV Mail - Main menu - Select message bases"

  SMB is a new style Select Message Base door for DayDream.
It offers you an easy way to configure which message bases you want to DL.

 All needed commands will be shown if you pres 'H' in SMB menu during use.

Flags in front of MSG/Conf name means 

 -  = You are not allowed to enter this conf/base
 A  = You will dl all messages from this base
 P  = You will dl personal only messages from this base
 F  = You are forced to download messages from this base

@endnode

@node "main.q" "MV Mail - Main menu - Quit door and back to BBS"

 This option simply quit door and put user back to BBS main prompt.

@endnode

